Can We Predict Patterns of Hospitalizations Across States?

Bracken Sant

library(mosaic)
library(pander)
library(car)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(rio)
library(alr4)
library(lubridate)

Introduction

We will be exploring Covid-19 data from two states, California and New York. I will make a model for both California and New York to predict the number of Hospitalizations, due to covid, based off of the case count and other variables from 7 days prior. With this I hope to be able to help hospitals be more prepared for big surges so that they will be able to assist more people and wont be as overworked.

New York Data and Model

vacs <- read_csv("vaccinations.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

hosp <- read_csv("hospitalizations.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

ny_data <- import("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nychealth/coronavirus-data/master/trends/data-by-day.csv") %>% 
  mutate(
    date_of_interest = mdy(date_of_interest)
  ) %>% 
  select(date_of_interest, CASE_COUNT, HOSPITALIZED_COUNT, DEATH_COUNT)



vacs_ny <- vacs %>% 
  filter(location_key == "US_NY")

hosp_ny <- hosp %>% 
  filter(location_key == "US_NY")

vacs_hosp_all_ny_data <- hosp_ny %>% 
  left_join(vacs_ny, join_by("location_key"=="location_key", "date"=="date"))



data_all_ny <- ny_data %>%  left_join(vacs_hosp_all_ny_data, join_by("date_of_interest"=="date")) %>% 
  fill(c("new_persons_vaccinated", "new_persons_fully_vaccinated", "new_vaccine_doses_administered", "cumulative_persons_vaccinated", "cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated", "cumulative_vaccine_doses_administered"), .direction="down") %>% 
  replace_na(replace = list("new_hospitalized_patients" = 0,
                            "current_hospitalized_patients" = 0,
                            "new_ventilator_patients" = 0, "current_ventilator_patients" = 0,
                            "new_persons_vaccinated" = 0,"new_persons_fully_vaccinated" = 0,
                            "new_vaccine_doses_administered" = 0, "CASE_COUNT" = 0, "HOSPITALIZED_COUNT" = 0,
                            "DEATH_COUNT" = 0, "cumulative_hospitalized_patients" = 0,
                            "cumulative_ventilator_patients" = 0, 
                            "cumulative_persons_vaccinated" = 0, "cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated" = 0,
                            "cumulative_vaccine_doses_administered" = 0)) %>%
  select(-contains("pfizer"), -contains("moderna"), -contains("janssen"),
         -contains("sinovac"), -c("location_key"), -contains("intensive"),
         -c("new_ventilator_patients", "location_key", "cumulative_ventilator_patients"),
         -contains("vaccine_doses"))



cases <- data_all_ny %>% select(date_of_interest, HOSPITALIZED_COUNT)
everything_else <- data_all_ny %>% select(!c(HOSPITALIZED_COUNT))

everything_else_up7 <- everything_else  %>% mutate(
  date_of_interest = lubridate::as_date(date_of_interest) + 7
)

adjusted_dates_complete <- cases %>% left_join(everything_else_up7, by="date_of_interest")
adjusted_dates_complete <- adjusted_dates_complete[8:930, ] %>% 
  mutate(
    full_vacs_G_mean = factor(ifelse(cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated > mean(cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated), "fullVacs>Mean", "fullVacs<Mean")),
    ventilator_patients = factor(ifelse(current_ventilator_patients > 0, "VentPat", "NoVentPat"))
  ) %>% 
  select(date_of_interest, HOSPITALIZED_COUNT, CASE_COUNT, full_vacs_G_mean, ventilator_patients, cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated, current_ventilator_patients)

Data Set Information

  • The HOSPITALIZED_COUNT and CASE_COUNT columns come from this link and show the count of hospitalizations and cases for covid-19 on a given day.

  • The full_vacs_G_mean column is a True/False factor that shows if the cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated is greater than its mean, in this case the mean was a little over 7 million.

  • The ventilator_patients column is a True/False factor that shows if there are patients on a ventilator in the hospital given by this column current_ventilator_patients.

  • The full_vacs_G_mean and ventilator_patients are never both True at the same time in the data set.

  • All of the columns besides HOSPITALIZED_COUNT are set forward by 7 days, so we are using data from 7 days prior to predict the HOSPITALIZED_COUNT. I chose 7 days because that was the average time it took to display symptoms after being infected. cdc

The other Data in the table I got from Covid Vaccine and Specific Hospital Data Sets.

DT::datatable(adjusted_dates_complete %>% select(date_of_interest, HOSPITALIZED_COUNT, CASE_COUNT, full_vacs_G_mean, ventilator_patients))

Making the Model

lm_covid_ny_non <- lm(HOSPITALIZED_COUNT~(CASE_COUNT) + CASE_COUNT:full_vacs_G_mean + CASE_COUNT:ventilator_patients, adjusted_dates_complete)

boxCox(lm_covid_ny_non)

The \(\lambda\) appears to be close to 0, so we will make a log transformation.

lm_covid_ny <- lm(log(HOSPITALIZED_COUNT)~(CASE_COUNT) + CASE_COUNT:full_vacs_G_mean + CASE_COUNT:ventilator_patients, adjusted_dates_complete)
summary(lm_covid_ny)

b_ny <- coef(lm_covid_ny)

All of the features used show significant p-values below 0.001, so they would be able to be used even with the lowest significance level on the summary. The R-squared is around .63 which shows a moderate to strong correlation and by looking at the slope estimates we can see that it is a positive correlation between CASE_COUNT and HOSPITALIZED_COUNT.

The cumulative full vaccinations > 7 million appears to be very meaningful as well as the variable of if the state had ventilator patients in hospitals. I believe that it might not be as much about the vaccinations as it was about the timing of when the cumulative full vaccinations rose above 7 million, which was 2021-05-14. This is when cold and flu type viruses usually taper off because temperatures start to rise and there arent as many fluctuations to the weather. This is also about a year after the pandemic began and when people would start building an immunity to it naturally; however, the vaccinations might have been a factor as well. The same with ventilator patients in hospitals which appeared to only be at the beginning of the pandemic and before the cumulative full vaccinations rose above 7 million.

plot(lm_covid_ny, which=c(5))

Explanation:

In the Cooks distance graph above, none of the points go out of the .5 bounds so I will not make any adjustments to the data.

Graphing the Model

drawit_ny <- function(CASE_COUNT, fullVacsMean = 0, VentPat = 0){
  exp(b_ny[1] + b_ny[2]*CASE_COUNT + b_ny[3]*CASE_COUNT*fullVacsMean + b_ny[4]*CASE_COUNT*VentPat)
}

get_pred <- function(fullVacsMean = "fullVacs<Mean", VentPat = "NoVentPat"){
  CASE_COUNT <- seq(0, max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT), 4000)
  fullVacs_list <- rep(c(fullVacsMean),(max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT)/4000)+1)
  VentPat_list <- rep(c(VentPat),(max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT)/4000)+1)
  
  allpreds <- exp(predict(lm_covid_ny, data.frame(CASE_COUNT=CASE_COUNT, full_vacs_G_mean=fullVacs_list, ventilator_patients = VentPat_list), interval="prediction"))
  
  allpreds <- data.frame(allpreds, CASE_COUNT = CASE_COUNT, fullVacsMean = fullVacs_list, VentPat = VentPat_list)
  
  return(allpreds)
}

allpreds_blue <- get_pred("fullVacs<Mean", "NoVentPat")
allpreds_black <- get_pred("fullVacs>Mean", "NoVentPat")
allpreds_red <- get_pred("fullVacs<Mean", "VentPat")


ggplot(adjusted_dates_complete, aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=HOSPITALIZED_COUNT)) +
  geom_line(data=allpreds_blue, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=lwr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="skyblue", linewidth=1, alpha=.3) +
  geom_line(data=allpreds_blue, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=upr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="skyblue", linewidth=1, alpha=.3) +
  geom_line(data=allpreds_black, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=lwr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="black", linewidth=1, alpha=.3) +
  geom_line(data=allpreds_black, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=upr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="black", linewidth=1, alpha=.3) +
  geom_line(data=allpreds_red, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=lwr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="firebrick", linewidth=1, alpha=.3) +
  geom_line(data=allpreds_red, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=upr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="firebrick", linewidth=1, alpha=.3 ) +
  geom_point(aes(color=interaction(full_vacs_G_mean, ventilator_patients)), alpha=.3, size=3) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("skyblue", "black", "firebrick")) +
  stat_function(fun=drawit_ny, args=list(fullVacsMean=0, VentPat=0), aes(color="fullVacs<Mean.NoVentPat", linetype="LM"), linewidth=1) +
  stat_function(fun=drawit_ny, args=list(fullVacsMean=1, VentPat=0), aes(color="fullVacs>Mean.NoVentPat", linetype="LM"), linewidth=1) +
  stat_function(fun=drawit_ny, args=list(fullVacsMean=0, VentPat=1), aes(color="fullVacs<Mean.VentPat", linetype="LM"), linewidth=1) +
  guides(color=guide_legend(title="Case Count Lines")) +
  scale_linetype_manual(values=c("Confidence Interval" = 2, "LM" = 1)) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,2000)) +
  # facet_wrap(~interaction(full_vacs_G_mean, ventilator_patients)) +
  labs(
    x = "Covid Case Count (7 Days Prior)",
    y = "Hospitalized",
    title = "New York Covid Case Counts and Hospitalizations",
    subtitle = "March 2020 - September 2022"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        title = element_text(hjust=.5))

New York Model Explanation

I decided to look at two different parts of the graph for this since it can have varying slopes based on where it is on the graph.

Blue Line: When the amount of full vaccinations is not greater than the mean in the data set and there are not patients in the hospital on a ventilator (both 7 days prior to hospitalization predictions), the predicted count of hospitalizations, due to covid, for that day go up by (from 1 to 2 covid cases) \(0.0341588\) per additional covid case 7 days prior. This means that it estimates for every 33 additional cases it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

From 3500 to 3501 covid cases \(0.2846782\) per additional covid case 7 days prior. This means that it estimates for about every 4 additional cases it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

Black Line: When the amount of full vaccinations is greater than the mean in the data set but there are not patients in the hospital on a ventilator (both 7 days prior to hospitalization predictions), the predicted count of hospitalizations, due to covid, for that day go up by (from 1 to 2 covid cases) \(0.0050349\) per additional covid case 7 days prior. This means that it estimates for every 200 additional cases, at the beginning, it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

From 25000 to 25001 covid cases for this \(0.0470406\) per additional covid case 7 days prior. This means that it estimates for every 20 to 22 additional cases, at the beginning, it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

Red Line: When there are patients on a ventilator in the hospital but the amount of full vaccinations is not greater than the mean in the data set (both 7 days prior to hospitalization predictions), the predicted count of hospitalizations, due to covid, for that day go up by (from 1 to 2 covid cases) \(0.0243923\) per additional covid case 7 days prior. This means that it estimates for every 50 additional cases it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

From 4000 to 4001 covid cases \(0.1377146\) per additional covid case 7 days prior. This means that it estimates for every 7 to 8 additional cases it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

Confidence Intervals: The only confidence interval that appears to be large and changes in size is for the black confidence interval. This makes sense as the data points vary a lot more. The blue and red confidence intervals stay relatively the same throughout and are relatively small, this might be due to the small range of points compared to the black data points.

Explanation

There seems to be a megaphone shape in the Residuals, so it fails the constant variance test for the residuals. We will continue with the test, however. We will just not be able to reach any conclusions from the results. The results for this test look better in our non-transformed model, though it appears that there are some worrying points at the top (30, 31, 32).

California Data and Model

cases_cali <- read_csv("cases_cali.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>% group_by(date) %>% summarise(probable_cases = sum(probable_cases))

hospit_cali <- read_csv("hospital_cali.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>% replace_na(replace = list(hospitalized_covid_confirmed_patients = 0, hospitalized_suspected_covid_patients = 0)) %>% group_by(todays_date) %>% summarise(hospitalized_covid_confirmed_patients = sum(hospitalized_covid_confirmed_patients),
          hospitalized_suspected_covid_patients = sum(hospitalized_suspected_covid_patients))

cali_hosp_cases <- hospit_cali %>% left_join(cases_cali, join_by(todays_date == date))



hosp_cali <- hosp %>% 
  filter(location_key == "US_CA")

vacs_cali <- vacs %>% 
  filter(location_key == "US_CA")

vacs_hosp_all_cali_data <- hosp_cali %>% 
  left_join(vacs_cali, join_by("location_key"=="location_key", "date"=="date"))



data_all_cali <- cali_hosp_cases %>%  left_join(vacs_hosp_all_cali_data, join_by("todays_date"=="date")) %>% 
  fill(c("new_persons_vaccinated", "new_persons_fully_vaccinated", "new_vaccine_doses_administered", "cumulative_persons_vaccinated", "cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated", "cumulative_vaccine_doses_administered"), .direction="down") %>% 
  replace_na(replace = list("new_hospitalized_patients" = 0, "current_hospitalized_patients" = 0,
                            "new_ventilator_patients" = 0, "current_ventilator_patients" = 0,
                            "new_persons_vaccinated" = 0,"new_persons_fully_vaccinated" = 0,
                            "new_vaccine_doses_administered" = 0, "cumulative_hospitalized_patients" = 0,
                            "cumulative_ventilator_patients" = 0, "cumulative_persons_vaccinated" = 0,
                            "cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated" = 0, "cumulative_vaccine_doses_administered" = 0)) %>%
  select(-contains("pfizer"), -contains("moderna"), -contains("janssen"),
         -contains("sinovac"), -c("location_key"), -contains("intensive"),
         -c("new_ventilator_patients", "location_key", "cumulative_ventilator_patients"),

Data Set Information

  • The hospitalized_covid_confirmed_patients and probable_cases columns come from these links (hospital, cases) and show the count of hospitalizations and cases for covid-19 on a given day.

  • The full_vacs_G_mean is a True/False factor that shows if the cumulative_persons_fully_vaccinated is greater than its mean, in this case the mean was a little over 17 million.

  • I also set this data set forward by 7 days with the same reasons as the New York Data.

  • I tried getting similar data to the New York data and even went on the California equivalent website, but the data doesnt seem to match up super well because the counts for hospitalizations is much higher and the case count is lower.

Graphing the Model

drawit_cali <- function(CASE_COUNT, fullVacsMean = 0){
  (b_cali[1] + b_cali[2]*CASE_COUNT + b_cali[3]*CASE_COUNT*fullVacsMean)^4
}

get_pred <- function(fullVacsMean = "fullVacs<Mean"){
  CASE_COUNT <- seq(0, max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT), 4000)
  fullVacs_list <- rep(c(fullVacsMean),(max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT)/4000)+1)
  
  allpreds <- (predict(lm_covid_cali, data.frame(CASE_COUNT=CASE_COUNT, full_vacs_G_mean=fullVacs_list), interval="prediction"))^4
  
  allpreds <- data.frame(allpreds, CASE_COUNT = CASE_COUNT, fullVacsMean = fullVacs_list)
  
  return(allpreds)
}

California Model Explanation

I decided to look at two different parts of the graph for this since it can have varying slopes based on where it is on the graph.

Blue Line: When the amount of full vaccinations is not greater than the mean in the data set (7 days prior to hospitalization predictions), the predicted count of hospitalizations, due to covid, go up by (from 1 to 2 covid cases) \(1.7667352\) per additional probable covid case.

From 3000 to 3001 covid cases \(6.3165154\) per additional probable covid case.

Black Line: When the amount of full vaccinations is greater than the mean in the data set (7 days prior to hospitalization predictions), the predicted count of hospitalizations, due to covid, go up by (from 1 to 2 covid cases) \(0.2815673\) per additional probable covid case. This means that it estimates for about every 4 additional cases it is predicted that there will be 1 additional hospitalization.

From 22500 to 22501 covid cases for this \(20.64864\) per additional covid case 7 days prior.

Additional Information These estimations are very different than the New York estimations, this may lead to a problem with validating across data sets.

Confidence Intervals: The confidence interval for the blue line appears to stay consistent with its width and is much smaller than the black confidence interval. The black confidence interval stays consistent like the other but is much wider and this makes sense because the black data points cover a much wider area than the blue.

Assumptions

par(mfcol=c(1,2))
plot(lm_covid_cali, which=1, main="Res vs Fitted Sqrt-Sqrt Trans.")
plot(lm_covid_cali_non, which=1, main="Res vs Fitted No Trans.")

Explanation

The residuals do not appear to have constant variance. This would normally lead to adding a quadratic element into the linear model; however, after making the graph it does not make sense to add this element. I will show the graph below and explain more. The residuals for the non-transformation also appears that it violates constant variance with a megaphone shape in the points.

lm_covid_cali2 <- lm(sqrt(sqrt(HOSPITALIZED_COUNT))~CASE_COUNT + CASE_COUNT:full_vacs_G_mean + I(CASE_COUNT^2):full_vacs_G_mean, adjusted_dates_complete_cali)

b_cali <- coef(lm_covid_cali2)

drawit_cali <- function(CASE_COUNT, fullVacsMean = 0){
  (b_cali[1] + b_cali[2]*CASE_COUNT + b_cali[3]*CASE_COUNT*fullVacsMean + b_cali[4]*CASE_COUNT^2*(fullVacsMean*-1+1) + b_cali[5]*CASE_COUNT^2*fullVacsMean)^4
}

get_pred <- function(fullVacsMean = "fullVacs<Mean"){
  CASE_COUNT <- seq(0, max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT), 4000)
  fullVacs_list <- rep(c(fullVacsMean),(max(adjusted_dates_complete$CASE_COUNT)/4000)+1)
  
  allpreds <- (predict(lm_covid_cali2, data.frame(CASE_COUNT=CASE_COUNT, full_vacs_G_mean=fullVacs_list), interval="prediction"))^4
  
  allpreds <- data.frame(allpreds, CASE_COUNT = CASE_COUNT, fullVacsMean = fullVacs_list)
  
  return(allpreds)
}

allpreds_blue <- get_pred("fullVacs<Mean")
allpreds_black <- get_pred("fullVacs>Mean")


ggplot(adjusted_dates_complete_cali, aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=HOSPITALIZED_COUNT)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=interaction(full_vacs_G_mean)), alpha=.3, size=3) +

  stat_function(fun=drawit_cali, args=list(fullVacsMean=1), aes(color="fullVacs>Mean", linetype="LM"), linewidth=1) +

  geom_line(data=allpreds_black, mapping=aes(x=CASE_COUNT, y=lwr, linetype="Confidence Interval"), color="black", linewidth=1, alpha=.3) +

While it does appear to fit the data better I feel like it may be over fitting the data, especially the black line. So I decided that it would be better to continue with the two-line model rather than to make a quadratic two-line model.

Validation for Models

set.seed(121)

num_rows <- 700 #1460 total
keep <- sample(1:nrow(adjusted_dates_complete), num_rows)

mytrain <- adjusted_dates_complete[keep, ] #Use this in the lm(..., data=mytrain) it is like "rbdata"

mytest <- adjusted_dates_complete[-keep, ] #Use this in the predict(..., newdata=mytest) it is like "rbdata2"

model <- lm(log(HOSPITALIZED_COUNT)~(CASE_COUNT) + CASE_COUNT:full_vacs_G_mean + CASE_COUNT:ventilator_patients, data=mytrain)
model_non <- lm(HOSPITALIZED_COUNT~(CASE_COUNT) + CASE_COUNT:full_vacs_G_mean + CASE_COUNT:ventilator_patients, data=mytrain)

thedata2 <- mytest
# Get y-hat for each model on new data.
yme <- exp(predict(model, newdata=thedata2))
yme_non <- (predict(model_non, newdata=thedata2))

# Compute y-bar
ybar <- (mean(thedata2$HOSPITALIZED_COUNT)) #Yi is given by Ynew from the new sample of data

# Compute SSTO
SSTO <- sum((thedata2$HOSPITALIZED_COUNT - ybar)^2)

# Compute SSE for each model using y - yhat
SSEme <- sum((thedata2$HOSPITALIZED_COUNT - yme)^2)
SSEme_non <- sum((thedata2$HOSPITALIZED_COUNT - yme_non)^2)

# Compute R-squared for each
rsme <- 1 - SSEme/SSTO
rsme_non <- 1 - SSEme_non/SSTO

# Compute adjusted R-squared for each
n <- length(thedata2$HOSPITALIZED_COUNT) #sample size
pme <- length(coef(model)) #num. parameters in model
rsmea <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-pme)*SSEme/SSTO
pme_non <- length(coef(model_non)) #num. parameters in model
rsmea_non <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-pme_non)*SSEme_non/SSTO
  

my_output_table2 <- data.frame(Model = c("New York Model Log Trans.", "New York Model Non Trans."), `Original R2` = c(summary(model)$r.squared, summary(model_non)$r.squared), `Orig. Adj. R-squared` = c(summary(model)$adj.r.squared, summary(model_non)$adj.r.squared), `Validation R-squared` = c(rsme, rsme_non), `Validation Adj. R^2` = c(rsmea, rsmea_non))

colnames(my_output_table2) <- c("Model", "Original $R^2$", "Original Adj. $R^2$", "Validation $R^2$", "Validation Adj. $R^2$")

knitr::kable(my_output_table2, escape=TRUE, digits=4)

New York Model Log Trans. 0.6168 0.6152 -1.4786 -1.5126
New York Model Non Trans. 0.6475 0.6460 0.6787 0.6743
